narratives.question_text:
What knowledge, skills, and insights did you develop by taking this course?
(Your anonymous response to this question may be viewed by Yale College students, faculty, and advisers to aid in course selection and evaluating teaching.)
comments: I developed new insights into things I had learned before such as Taylor series, polar functions, and parametric functions.
I learned the basics of Calculus 2integrals, volumes, parametrics/polar equations.

narratives.question_text:
What are the strengths and weaknesses of this course and how could it be improved?
(Your anonymous response to this question may be viewed by Yale College students, faculty, and advisers to aid in course selection and evaluating teaching.)
comments: I think that the lectures should have been recorded for easier access for students, but I believe the review sessions before exams helped alot.

Strengths: there is a lot of practice problems/tests assigned and the psets really do help develop knowledge of the course material 
Weaknesses: the quality of lessons is highly dependent on what instructor you have teaching your course; some are not very engaged during class and especially in a virtual format it was difficult to adequately go through problems/work as a class
Strengths: Lots of opportunity to practice with concepts, support from peer tutors and instructors. Weaknesses: Exams count a lot toward final grade.

narratives.question_text: Among the practices in this course geared toward learning during the COVID-19 pandemic, which succeeded and which could be improved? Please comment on course practices that allowed for virtual engagement. (Your anonymous response to this question may be viewed by Yale College students, faculty, and advisers to aid in course selection and evaluating teaching.)
comments: I feel that the instructor could have engaged the class more and waited for questions/answers rather than moving on quickly.

The course did a good job of providing practice tests/problems to prep for exams. I found that putting us in breakout rooms to do practice problems wasn't super helpful because we would often be confused as a group and it was difficult to collaborate/ask questions in that setting. Also, it felt like we were mainly being lectured and not super engaged with the course material.

narratives.question_text:
Would you recommend this course to another student? Please explain.
(Your anonymous response to this question may be viewed by Yale College students, faculty, and advisers to aid in course selection and evaluating teaching.)
comments: I would if you are pre med and need to take a math class but do not want to take Math 120. Take it if you have taken BC Calculus already.
Yes, if you like math or need to complete a calculus prereq, I would take it
